1
00:03:17,522 --> 00:03:20,859
- Sir.
- General.

2
00:03:20,942 --> 00:03:23,236
- General.
- Sir.

3
00:03:23,320 --> 00:03:25,489
General.

4
00:03:25,530 --> 00:03:27,616
-Sir.
- General.

5
00:03:27,699 --> 00:03:29,284
General.

6
00:03:29,368 --> 00:03:31,953
- Sir.

7
00:03:47,177 --> 00:03:49,388
Lean and hungry.

8
00:03:51,932 --> 00:03:54,810
- Still nothing?
- Not a sign.

9
00:03:54,893 --> 00:03:57,771
- How long has he been gone?
- Nearly two hours.

10
00:04:00,732 --> 00:04:03,777
- Will they fight, sir?
- We shall know soon enough.

11
00:04:03,860 --> 00:04:06,488
Soldier, I ordered you
to move those catapults forward.

12
00:04:06,571 --> 00:04:10,075
- They're out of range.
- Range is good.

13
00:04:10,158 --> 00:04:13,620
- The danger to the cavalry-
- It is acceptable. Agreed?

14
00:04:23,004 --> 00:04:24,965
They say no.

15
00:04:34,057 --> 00:04:36,518
- Steady! Steady!

16
00:04:50,657 --> 00:04:52,743
People should know
when they're conquered.

17
00:05:03,837 --> 00:05:07,758
Would you, Quintus?
Would l?

18
00:05:22,856 --> 00:05:25,108
Strength and honor.

19
00:05:25,192 --> 00:05:27,736
- Strength and honor.
- Strength and honor.

20
00:05:32,949 --> 00:05:35,869
At my signal,
unleash hell.

21
00:05:58,683 --> 00:06:01,978
Load the catapults.

22
00:06:02,062 --> 00:06:04,481
Infantry form up
for advance.

23
00:06:04,564 --> 00:06:06,942
- Archers ready.
- Archers!

24
00:06:07,025 --> 00:06:08,819
- Knock!
- Knock!

25
00:06:32,509 --> 00:06:35,804
- Patres!
- Maximus!

26
00:06:37,431 --> 00:06:41,101
Three weeks from now,
I will be harvesting my crops.

27
00:06:41,184 --> 00:06:45,647
Imagine where you will be,
and it will be so.

28
00:06:46,732 --> 00:06:49,943
Hold the line!
Stay with me!

29
00:06:50,026 --> 00:06:52,738
If you find yourself alone,

30
00:06:52,821 --> 00:06:55,449
riding in green fields
with the sun on your face,

31
00:06:57,075 --> 00:06:59,953
do not be troubled.

32
00:06:59,995 --> 00:07:03,665
For you are in Elysium,
and you're already dead!

33
00:07:06,001 --> 00:07:07,669
Brothers,

34
00:07:08,837 --> 00:07:11,715
what we do in life...

35
00:07:11,798 --> 00:07:13,759
echoes in eternity.

36
00:07:20,682 --> 00:07:23,018
- Pull!

37
00:07:30,859 --> 00:07:33,737
Pull! Pull!

38
00:07:38,658 --> 00:07:40,702
Catapults ready, sir!

39
00:07:51,630 --> 00:07:53,924
Archers, ignite!

40
00:07:54,007 --> 00:07:56,593
- Ignite!
- Ignite!

41
00:08:02,349 --> 00:08:05,060
Archers, draw!

42
00:08:07,813 --> 00:08:09,773
Loose!

43
00:08:11,358 --> 00:08:13,944
Loose!

44
00:08:21,201 --> 00:08:23,161
Aah!

45
00:08:23,203 --> 00:08:25,330
Aah!

46
00:08:30,836 --> 00:08:33,296
- Aah!
- Aah!

47
00:08:39,010 --> 00:08:42,013
All right, men, ready!

48
00:08:46,518 --> 00:08:48,937
Hold the line!

49
00:08:54,609 --> 00:08:57,237
Draw! Loose!

50
00:08:57,320 --> 00:08:59,489
Loose! Loose!

51
00:08:59,573 --> 00:09:01,491
Reload!

52
00:09:05,787 --> 00:09:08,040
Hold the line!

53
00:09:08,123 --> 00:09:10,417
Draw! Loose!

54
00:09:13,086 --> 00:09:15,797
Stay with me!

55
00:09:19,634 --> 00:09:22,429
Stay with me!

56
00:09:50,207 --> 00:09:53,126
Roma Victor!

57
00:10:09,768 --> 00:10:11,603
Aah!

58
00:10:21,071 --> 00:10:23,490
Aah!

59
00:10:37,170 --> 00:10:39,464
Aah!

60
00:10:44,928 --> 00:10:47,264
Aah!

61
00:10:49,182 --> 00:10:51,476
Aah!

62
00:11:08,410 --> 00:11:10,454
Aah!

63
00:11:15,584 --> 00:11:18,545
Aah!

64
00:11:45,238 --> 00:11:47,157
Aah!

65
00:12:26,279 --> 00:12:28,281
Roma Victor!

66
00:13:10,323 --> 00:13:12,951
Do you think
he's really dying?

67
00:13:13,994 --> 00:13:15,996
He's been dying
for ten years.

68
00:13:16,079 --> 00:13:19,291
If he weren't really dying,
he wouldn't have sent for us.

69
00:13:20,500 --> 00:13:22,544
Maybe he just
misses us.

70
00:13:22,627 --> 00:13:25,380
And the senators?
He wouldn't have summoned them if-

71
00:13:25,464 --> 00:13:27,382
Peace, Commodus.

72
00:13:27,466 --> 00:13:31,053
After two weeks on the road, your
incessant scheming is hurting my head.

73
00:13:37,392 --> 00:13:39,394
He's made
his decision.

74
00:13:39,478 --> 00:13:41,897
He's going to announce it.

75
00:13:45,067 --> 00:13:46,985
He will name me.

76
00:13:49,738 --> 00:13:52,574
The first thing I shall do...

77
00:13:52,657 --> 00:13:54,576
when-

78
00:13:56,370 --> 00:14:00,040
is honor him with games
worthy of His Majesty.

79
00:14:00,082 --> 00:14:04,544
For now, the first thing
I shall do is have a bath.

80
00:14:04,628 --> 00:14:08,006
- Your Highness?

81
00:14:10,175 --> 00:14:13,345
We seem to be almost there, sir.

82
00:14:19,142 --> 00:14:22,062
- Sire.
- Where's the Emperor?

83
00:14:22,145 --> 00:14:25,273
He's at the front, sire.
They've been gone for 1 9 days.

84
00:14:25,315 --> 00:14:28,110
The wounded are
still coming in.

85
00:14:28,151 --> 00:14:30,112
My horse.

86
00:14:30,153 --> 00:14:32,114
My lord.

87
00:14:34,783 --> 00:14:37,202
Kiss?

88
00:15:11,528 --> 00:15:13,447
You have proved
your valor...

89
00:15:13,530 --> 00:15:16,658
yet again, Maximus.

90
00:15:17,951 --> 00:15:20,704
Let us hope
for the last time.

91
00:15:20,787 --> 00:15:23,582
There's no one
left to fight, sire.

92
00:15:23,665 --> 00:15:26,126
Ah. There is always
someone left to fight.

93
00:15:26,209 --> 00:15:29,129
How can I reward
Rome's greatest general?

94
00:15:34,551 --> 00:15:37,137
Let me go home.

95
00:15:37,220 --> 00:15:39,890
Ah. Home.

96
00:15:46,396 --> 00:15:48,315
Whoa! Whoa!

97
00:15:58,075 --> 00:16:00,202
They honor you, Caesar.

98
00:16:00,285 --> 00:16:03,205
It's for you, Maximus.
They honor you.

99
00:16:25,811 --> 00:16:28,772
Have I missed it?
Have I missed the battle?

100
00:16:28,814 --> 00:16:31,525
You have
missed the war.

101
00:16:31,608 --> 00:16:33,944
Father, congratulations.

102
00:16:34,027 --> 00:16:36,947
I shall sacrifice a hundred bulls
to honor your triumph.

103
00:16:37,030 --> 00:16:39,032
Save the bulls.

104
00:16:39,116 --> 00:16:41,284
Honor Maximus.
He won the battle.

105
00:16:41,368 --> 00:16:44,371
- General.
- Highness.

106
00:16:44,454 --> 00:16:48,750
Rome salutes you,
and I embrace you as a brother.

107
00:16:48,792 --> 00:16:51,086
It has been too long,
my old friend.

108
00:16:51,128 --> 00:16:53,255
- Highness.
- Here, Father.

109
00:16:53,296 --> 00:16:55,632
Take my arm.

110
00:16:56,800 --> 00:16:59,720
I think it is time
for me to leave.

111
00:17:14,484 --> 00:17:17,904
So much for
the glory of Rome.

112
00:17:38,717 --> 00:17:40,635
Magnificent battle.

113
00:18:04,117 --> 00:18:06,078
- General.
- Still alive?

114
00:18:06,119 --> 00:18:09,164
-Still alive.
- The gods must have a sense of humor.

115
00:18:09,247 --> 00:18:11,917
- The gods must love you.
- Valerius.

116
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:14,544
Back to barracks, General?
Or to Rome?

117
00:18:14,628 --> 00:18:17,714
Home. My wife,
the son, the harvest.

118
00:18:17,798 --> 00:18:21,927
Maximus the farmer.
I still have difficulty imagining that.

119
00:18:22,010 --> 00:18:25,639
You know, dirt cleans off a lot
easier than blood, Quintus.

120
00:18:25,722 --> 00:18:27,891
- Here he is.
- Highness.

121
00:18:27,974 --> 00:18:29,851
Senator Gaius,
Senator Falco.

122
00:18:29,935 --> 00:18:33,355
Beware of Gaius. He'll pour a honeyed
potion in your ear...

123
00:18:33,397 --> 00:18:36,191
and you'll wake up one day,
and all you'll say is,
" Republic, republic, republic."

124
00:18:36,274 --> 00:18:39,361
Well, why not?
Rome was founded as a republic.

125
00:18:39,444 --> 00:18:42,280
Yes, and in a republic
the senate has the power.

126
00:18:42,364 --> 00:18:44,783
But Senator Gaius isn't
influenced by that, of course.

127
00:18:44,866 --> 00:18:47,536
Where do you stand, General?
Emperor or senate?

128
00:18:47,577 --> 00:18:52,874
The soldier has the advantage
of being able to look
his enemy in the eye, Senator.

129
00:18:52,916 --> 00:18:56,962
Well, with an army behind you,
you could be extremely political.

130
00:18:57,045 --> 00:18:59,923
I warned you.
Now I shall save you. Senators.

131
00:19:09,099 --> 00:19:12,060
Maximus.

132
00:19:12,102 --> 00:19:14,980
I'm going to need
good men like you.

133
00:19:16,690 --> 00:19:19,568
How may I be of service,
Highness?

134
00:19:19,651 --> 00:19:22,529
You're a man who knows
what it is to command.

135
00:19:22,612 --> 00:19:26,074
You give your orders, the orders
are obeyed and the battle is won.

136
00:19:26,158 --> 00:19:30,787
But these senators scheme
and squabble and flatter and deceive.

137
00:19:30,829 --> 00:19:34,332
Maximus, we must save Rome
from the politicians, my friend.

138
00:19:34,416 --> 00:19:37,961
Can I count on you...
when the time comes?

139
00:19:43,675 --> 00:19:47,012
Highness, when your father releases me,
I intend to return home.

140
00:19:47,095 --> 00:19:51,224
Home?
Well, no one's earned it more.

141
00:19:51,308 --> 00:19:55,312
Don't get too comfortable.
I may call on you before long.

142
00:19:57,064 --> 00:20:00,192
Lucilla's here.
Did you know?

143
00:20:00,275 --> 00:20:03,153
She's not forgotten you.

144
00:20:03,236 --> 00:20:05,489
And now you're
the great man.

145
00:20:17,667 --> 00:20:20,545
If only you
had been born a man.

146
00:20:21,588 --> 00:20:23,590
What a caesar
you would have made.

147
00:20:25,592 --> 00:20:27,552
Father.

148
00:20:32,974 --> 00:20:34,935
You would have
been strong.

149
00:20:35,018 --> 00:20:38,105
I wonder,
would you have been just?

150
00:20:38,188 --> 00:20:40,816
I would have been
what you taught me to be.

151
00:20:40,899 --> 00:20:43,318
Oh.

152
00:20:43,402 --> 00:20:45,320
How was your journey?

153
00:20:45,404 --> 00:20:49,658
Long. Uncomfortable.
Why have I come?

154
00:20:49,700 --> 00:20:52,244
I need your help.
With your brother.

155
00:20:52,327 --> 00:20:54,454
Of course.

156
00:20:54,496 --> 00:20:56,456
He loves you.
He always has.

157
00:20:57,666 --> 00:21:00,627
And...

158
00:21:00,669 --> 00:21:04,131
he will need you now
more than ever.

159
00:21:08,510 --> 00:21:10,762
Enough of politics.

160
00:21:10,846 --> 00:21:15,183
Let us pretend that you
are a loving daughter...

161
00:21:15,225 --> 00:21:17,269
and I am a good father.

162
00:21:22,566 --> 00:21:26,111
This is a pleasant fiction,
isn't it?

163
00:21:38,331 --> 00:21:40,375
Good morning.

164
00:21:52,637 --> 00:21:55,599
I need three more horses.

165
00:22:05,275 --> 00:22:07,611
Two! Three!

166
00:22:07,652 --> 00:22:09,654
Four!

167
00:22:09,696 --> 00:22:12,366
One! Two!

168
00:22:28,048 --> 00:22:30,926
You sent for me, Caesar?

169
00:22:33,303 --> 00:22:35,222
Caesar?

170
00:22:35,305 --> 00:22:38,725
Tell me again, Maximus.

171
00:22:38,809 --> 00:22:41,728
Why are we here?

172
00:22:41,770 --> 00:22:44,731
For the glory
of the Empire, sire.

173
00:22:44,773 --> 00:22:46,733
Ah, yes.

174
00:22:47,818 --> 00:22:50,237
Ah, yes, I remember.

175
00:22:52,614 --> 00:22:55,242
Do you see that map,
Maximus?

176
00:22:55,283 --> 00:22:59,413
That is the world
which I created.

177
00:22:59,454 --> 00:23:01,790
For25years...

178
00:23:01,873 --> 00:23:06,670
I have conquered, spilt blood,
expanded the Empire.

179
00:23:06,753 --> 00:23:10,716
Since I became caesar,
I've known four years without war.

180
00:23:10,799 --> 00:23:13,093
Four years of peace in 20.

181
00:23:13,135 --> 00:23:15,929
And for what?

182
00:23:22,477 --> 00:23:26,022
I brought the sword.
Nothing more.

183
00:23:26,106 --> 00:23:28,775
Caesar, your life-

184
00:23:28,859 --> 00:23:31,945
Please.
Please don't call me that.

185
00:23:32,029 --> 00:23:34,781
Come. Please.

186
00:23:34,865 --> 00:23:37,034
Come sit.

187
00:23:37,117 --> 00:23:40,328
Let us talk together now-

188
00:23:40,412 --> 00:23:42,706
very simply-as men.

189
00:23:44,374 --> 00:23:48,045
Maximus... talk.

190
00:23:51,757 --> 00:23:54,551
Five thousand of my men
are out there in the freezing mud.

191
00:23:54,634 --> 00:23:57,054
Three thousand of them
are bloodied and cleaved.

192
00:23:57,137 --> 00:23:59,222
Two thousand will never
leave this place.

193
00:23:59,306 --> 00:24:01,767
I will not believe that they
fought and died for nothing.

194
00:24:01,808 --> 00:24:03,769
And what would you
believe, Maximus?

195
00:24:03,810 --> 00:24:07,064
They fought for you...
and for Rome.

196
00:24:07,147 --> 00:24:10,025
And what is Rome,
Maximus?

197
00:24:11,109 --> 00:24:13,570
I've seen much of
the rest of the world.

198
00:24:13,612 --> 00:24:17,574
It is brutal and cruel and dark.
Rome is the light.

199
00:24:17,657 --> 00:24:19,701
Yet you have
never been there.

200
00:24:19,785 --> 00:24:22,204
You have not seen
what it has become.

201
00:24:22,287 --> 00:24:25,332
I am dying, Maximus.

202
00:24:25,415 --> 00:24:27,334
When a man sees his end,

203
00:24:27,417 --> 00:24:30,921
he wants to know there was
some purpose this life.

204
00:24:31,004 --> 00:24:34,633
How will the world speak my name
in years to come?

205
00:24:34,716 --> 00:24:37,052
Will I be known
as the philosopher?

206
00:24:37,135 --> 00:24:40,389
The warrior?
The tyrant?

207
00:24:41,848 --> 00:24:46,478
Or will I be the emperor who
gave Rome back her true self?

208
00:24:47,521 --> 00:24:49,648
There was once a dream
that was Rome.

209
00:24:49,689 --> 00:24:52,776
You could only
whisper it.

210
00:24:52,859 --> 00:24:55,862
Anything more than a whisper
and it would vanish.

211
00:24:55,946 --> 00:24:58,115
It was so fragile.

212
00:24:58,198 --> 00:25:01,868
And I fear that it will not
survive the winter.

213
00:25:03,412 --> 00:25:05,706
Maximus,

214
00:25:05,789 --> 00:25:08,709
Let us whisper now,

215
00:25:08,792 --> 00:25:11,044
together, you and l.

216
00:25:11,128 --> 00:25:13,797
You have a son.

217
00:25:13,880 --> 00:25:16,633
Tell me about your home.

218
00:25:22,597 --> 00:25:27,477
My house is in the hills above Tiujillo.
A very simple place.

219
00:25:28,979 --> 00:25:31,940
Pinkstones
that warm in the sun.

220
00:25:32,024 --> 00:25:36,028
A kitchen garden that
smells of herbs in the day,

221
00:25:36,111 --> 00:25:38,030
jasmine in the evening.

222
00:25:39,656 --> 00:25:42,617
Through the gate
is a giant poplar.

223
00:25:42,701 --> 00:25:45,537
Figs, apples, pears.

224
00:25:45,620 --> 00:25:47,539
The soil, Marcus-
black.

225
00:25:47,622 --> 00:25:50,459
- Black like my wife's hair.

226
00:25:50,500 --> 00:25:52,794
Grapes on the south slopes,
olives on the north.

227
00:25:52,836 --> 00:25:55,464
Wild ponies play near my house.
They tease my son.

228
00:25:55,505 --> 00:25:58,383
- He wants to be one of them.
- Remember the last time you were home?

229
00:25:58,467 --> 00:26:01,845
Two years, 264 days,
and this morning.

230
00:26:03,305 --> 00:26:05,682
I envy you, Maximus.

231
00:26:05,766 --> 00:26:09,478
It's a good home.
Worth fighting for.

232
00:26:11,605 --> 00:26:15,525
There is one more duty...

233
00:26:15,567 --> 00:26:18,862
that I ask of you
before you go home.

234
00:26:20,238 --> 00:26:22,491
What would you
have me do, Caesar?

235
00:26:22,574 --> 00:26:25,994
I want you to become
the protector of Rome after I die.

236
00:26:27,371 --> 00:26:30,374
I will empower you
to one end alone.

237
00:26:30,415 --> 00:26:34,711
To give power back
to the people of Rome...

238
00:26:34,753 --> 00:26:37,923
and end the corruption
that has crippled it.

239
00:26:44,054 --> 00:26:47,432
Will you accept this great honor
that I have offered you?

240
00:26:49,226 --> 00:26:52,229
With all my heart, no.

241
00:26:53,522 --> 00:26:55,816
Maximus,

242
00:26:55,899 --> 00:26:58,819
that is why
it must be you.

243
00:26:58,860 --> 00:27:00,821
But surely a prefect,
a senator,

244
00:27:00,862 --> 00:27:03,740
somebody who knows the city,
who understands her politics.

245
00:27:03,824 --> 00:27:06,785
But you have not been
corrupted by her politics.

246
00:27:11,832 --> 00:27:16,086
- And Commodus?
- Commodus is not a moral man.

247
00:27:16,169 --> 00:27:18,422
You have known that
since you were young.

248
00:27:18,505 --> 00:27:21,091
Commodus cannot rule.

249
00:27:21,174 --> 00:27:23,427
He must not rule.

250
00:27:24,803 --> 00:27:27,514
You are the son
that I should have had.

251
00:27:30,225 --> 00:27:33,687
Commodus will accept
my decision.

252
00:27:35,564 --> 00:27:40,235
He knows that you command
the loyalty of the army.

253
00:27:43,864 --> 00:27:46,950
I- I need
some time, sire.

254
00:27:47,034 --> 00:27:48,952
Yes.

255
00:27:49,036 --> 00:27:53,040
By sunset,
I hope you will have agreed.

256
00:27:53,123 --> 00:27:56,084
Now embrace me as my son.

257
00:27:58,795 --> 00:28:01,506
And bring an old man
another blanket.

258
00:28:17,230 --> 00:28:19,649
- My father favors you now.
- My lady.

259
00:28:19,733 --> 00:28:22,069
It was not always so.

260
00:28:22,152 --> 00:28:24,363
Many things change.

261
00:28:24,446 --> 00:28:27,240
Many things.
Not everything.

262
00:28:29,993 --> 00:28:31,995
Maximus, stop.

263
00:28:35,374 --> 00:28:38,335
Let me see your face.

264
00:28:38,377 --> 00:28:41,171
Hmm. You seem upset.

265
00:28:41,254 --> 00:28:43,382
I lost many men.

266
00:28:43,465 --> 00:28:46,301
What did my father
want with you?

267
00:28:46,385 --> 00:28:49,888
To wish me well
before I leave for home.

268
00:28:49,971 --> 00:28:52,015
You're lying.

269
00:28:52,099 --> 00:28:55,602
I could always tell when you were lying
because you were never any good at it.

270
00:28:55,685 --> 00:28:58,188
- I never acquired your comfort with it.
- True.

271
00:28:58,271 --> 00:29:00,857
But then you never had to.

272
00:29:00,941 --> 00:29:03,652
Life is more simple
for a soldier.

273
00:29:05,487 --> 00:29:08,740
Or do you
think me heartless?

274
00:29:08,782 --> 00:29:11,785
I think you have
a talent for survival.

275
00:29:17,499 --> 00:29:20,544
Maximus, stop.

276
00:29:20,627 --> 00:29:23,463
Is it really so terrible
seeing me again?

277
00:29:23,547 --> 00:29:27,259
No. I'm tired
from battle.

278
00:29:27,342 --> 00:29:30,137
It hurts you to see
my father so fragile.

279
00:29:33,306 --> 00:29:36,935
Commodus expects that my father will
announce his succession within days.

280
00:29:38,854 --> 00:29:42,315
Will you serve my brother
as you served his father?

281
00:29:44,401 --> 00:29:46,903
I will always serve Rome.

282
00:29:48,405 --> 00:29:50,365
Do you know,

283
00:29:50,407 --> 00:29:52,909
I still remember you
in my prayers.

284
00:29:53,994 --> 00:29:57,873
Oh, yes. I pray.

285
00:30:01,418 --> 00:30:04,379
I was sad to hear
of your husband's death. I mourned him.

286
00:30:06,590 --> 00:30:09,426
- Thank you.
- And I hear you have a son.

287
00:30:11,136 --> 00:30:14,556
Yes. Lucius.

288
00:30:14,598 --> 00:30:16,892
He'll be nearly
eight years old.

289
00:30:16,933 --> 00:30:19,519
My son is also
nearly eight.

290
00:30:22,147 --> 00:30:24,274
I thank you
for your prayers.

291
00:30:32,199 --> 00:30:36,036
Ancestors, I ask for your guidance.

292
00:30:36,119 --> 00:30:40,624
Blessed mother, come tome
with the gods' desire for my future.

293
00:30:40,707 --> 00:30:44,503
Blessed father, watch over
my wife and son with a ready sword.

294
00:30:46,254 --> 00:30:50,133
Whisper to them I live
only to hold them again.

295
00:30:50,175 --> 00:30:53,553
Ancestors, I honor you...

296
00:30:53,637 --> 00:30:57,057
and will try to live with
the dignity you have taught me.

297
00:31:18,954 --> 00:31:20,872
Cicero.

298
00:31:24,418 --> 00:31:27,087
Sir.

299
00:31:30,340 --> 00:31:33,051
You don't find it hard
to do your duty?

300
00:31:36,430 --> 00:31:39,725
Sometimes I do
what I want to do.

301
00:31:39,766 --> 00:31:42,561
The rest of the time
I do what I have to.

302
00:31:45,355 --> 00:31:48,275
We may not be able
to go home after all.

303
00:32:17,888 --> 00:32:21,058
Are you ready to do
your duty for Rome?

304
00:32:23,894 --> 00:32:26,355
Yes, Father.

305
00:32:26,396 --> 00:32:28,357
You will not be emperor.

306
00:32:31,193 --> 00:32:34,112
Which wiser,
older man is to take my place?

307
00:32:34,196 --> 00:32:37,491
My powers
will pass to Maximus...

308
00:32:37,574 --> 00:32:39,826
to hold
in trust...

309
00:32:39,910 --> 00:32:44,456
until the Senate
is ready to rule once more.

310
00:32:44,539 --> 00:32:49,294
Rome is to be
a republic again.

311
00:32:50,587 --> 00:32:53,715
- Maximus.
- Yes.

312
00:32:58,804 --> 00:33:01,264
My decision
disappoints you?

313
00:33:05,102 --> 00:33:08,939
You wrote to me once,

314
00:33:08,980 --> 00:33:12,859
Listing the four chief virtues.

315
00:33:12,943 --> 00:33:16,113
Wisdom, justice,

316
00:33:16,154 --> 00:33:19,491
fortitude and temperance.

317
00:33:21,993 --> 00:33:25,997
As I read the list,
I knew I had none of them.

318
00:33:26,081 --> 00:33:29,626
But I have other virtues, Father.

319
00:33:29,710 --> 00:33:32,295
Ambition.

320
00:33:32,379 --> 00:33:35,340
That can be a virtue
when it drives us to excel.

321
00:33:36,675 --> 00:33:40,053
Resourcefulness.
Courage.

322
00:33:40,137 --> 00:33:43,348
Perhaps not on
the battlefield, but...

323
00:33:43,390 --> 00:33:46,685
there are many forms of courage.

324
00:33:46,768 --> 00:33:50,022
Devotion-
to my family...

325
00:33:50,105 --> 00:33:52,649
and to you.

326
00:33:53,900 --> 00:33:57,362
But none of my virtues
were on your list.

327
00:33:58,864 --> 00:34:01,783
Even then it was as if
you didn't want me for your son.

328
00:34:01,867 --> 00:34:04,369
Oh, Commodus.

329
00:34:04,453 --> 00:34:07,164
You go too far.

330
00:34:07,247 --> 00:34:10,834
I search the faces
of the gods...

331
00:34:10,917 --> 00:34:15,672
for ways to please you,
to make you proud.

332
00:34:15,756 --> 00:34:18,091
One kind word,

333
00:34:18,175 --> 00:34:20,510
one full hug...

334
00:34:20,594 --> 00:34:25,432
where you pressed me
to your chest and held me tight,

335
00:34:25,515 --> 00:34:28,477
would have been like the sun
on my heart for a thousand years.

336
00:34:31,646 --> 00:34:34,816
- What is it in me you hate so much?
- Shah, Commodus.

337
00:34:36,693 --> 00:34:38,945
All I've ever wanted...

338
00:34:39,029 --> 00:34:43,533
was to live up to you,
Caesar.

339
00:34:44,618 --> 00:34:46,536
Father.

340
00:34:46,620 --> 00:34:49,206
Commodus.

341
00:34:51,541 --> 00:34:54,669
Your faults as a son...

342
00:34:54,711 --> 00:34:58,673
is my failure as a father.

343
00:35:08,725 --> 00:35:11,478
Come.

344
00:35:13,897 --> 00:35:16,316
Father.

345
00:35:30,622 --> 00:35:33,792
I would butcher
the whole world...

346
00:35:33,875 --> 00:35:36,586
if you would
only love me!

347
00:36:13,707 --> 00:36:17,794
Maximus, the Emperor needs you.
It's urgent.

348
00:36:22,549 --> 00:36:26,803
Lament with me, brother.
Our great father is dead.

349
00:36:54,164 --> 00:36:56,958
How did he die?

350
00:36:57,042 --> 00:36:59,711
The surgeons say there was no pain.

351
00:36:59,795 --> 00:37:01,880
His breath gave out
as he slept.

352
00:37:11,056 --> 00:37:12,974
Father.

353
00:37:15,352 --> 00:37:17,979
Your emperor asks
for your loyalty, Maximus.

354
00:37:19,606 --> 00:37:22,067
Take my hand.

355
00:37:23,944 --> 00:37:26,738
I only offer it once.

356
00:37:40,001 --> 00:37:41,920
Quintus.

357
00:38:31,511 --> 00:38:33,805
Hail, Caesar.

358
00:38:33,847 --> 00:38:36,641
I must go to the senators.
I need their counsel.

359
00:38:36,683 --> 00:38:39,269
- Wake Gaius and Falco.
- Gaius and Falco.

360
00:38:39,353 --> 00:38:41,563
- Sword.
- Sword.

361
00:38:43,190 --> 00:38:46,568
Maximus, please be careful.
That was not prudent.

362
00:38:46,651 --> 00:38:50,030
Prudent?
The Emperor has been slain.

363
00:38:50,072 --> 00:38:53,325
The Emperor died of natural causes.

364
00:38:53,408 --> 00:38:56,411
- Why are you armed, Quintus?
- Guards!

365
00:38:59,581 --> 00:39:01,875
Please don't fight,
Maximus.

366
00:39:03,168 --> 00:39:06,213
I'm sorry. Caesar has spoken.

367
00:39:06,254 --> 00:39:10,842
Ride until dawn...
and then execute him.

368
00:39:10,926 --> 00:39:13,345
Quintus, look at me.
Look at me!

369
00:39:13,428 --> 00:39:16,515
Promise me that you will
look after my family.

370
00:39:17,682 --> 00:39:20,268
Your family will meet you
in the afterlife.

371
00:39:20,352 --> 00:39:21,603
- No!

372
00:39:45,669 --> 00:39:48,171
Kneel.

373
00:39:50,924 --> 00:39:53,301
Blessed Father,
watch over my wife and son.

374
00:39:53,343 --> 00:39:55,470
- Whisper to them that I live
only to hold them again.

375
00:39:58,056 --> 00:40:00,559
At least give me
a clean death.

376
00:40:00,685 --> 00:40:02,604
A soldier's death.

377
00:40:23,917 --> 00:40:27,420
The frost, sometimes it makes
the blade stick.

378
00:40:47,983 --> 00:40:49,943
Praetorian!

379
00:40:51,194 --> 00:40:53,780
Hyah! Hyah!

380
00:42:08,396 --> 00:42:11,316
Remember the last time you were home?

381
00:42:11,399 --> 00:42:15,946
Two years, 264 days, and this morning.

382
00:42:16,029 --> 00:42:20,367
Blessed Father, watch over my
wife and son with a ready sword.

383
00:42:20,450 --> 00:42:23,787
Whisper to them I live only
to hold them again.

384
00:42:23,870 --> 00:42:27,207
For all else is dust and air,
and I live only to hold them again.

385
00:42:28,542 --> 00:42:31,545
For all else is dust and air.

386
00:43:08,582 --> 00:43:11,960
- Mama, isoldati!

387
00:43:30,604 --> 00:43:32,814
- Papa! Papa!

388
00:43:38,069 --> 00:43:40,655
Hyah! Hyah!

389
00:46:17,229 --> 00:46:20,315
- Don't die.

390
00:46:25,153 --> 00:46:27,405
- You'll meet them again.

391
00:46:27,489 --> 00:46:30,700
- Not yet.

392
00:46:38,416 --> 00:46:42,879
No! They will clean it.
Wait and see.

393
00:47:16,663 --> 00:47:18,748
Don't die.

394
00:47:18,832 --> 00:47:21,167
They'll feed you
to the lions.

395
00:47:21,209 --> 00:47:23,211
They are worth more
than we are.

396
00:47:33,930 --> 00:47:35,974
Better now?

397
00:47:36,057 --> 00:47:38,018
Clean. You see?

398
00:48:08,673 --> 00:48:10,592
Proximo!

399
00:48:10,675 --> 00:48:13,178
My old friend.

400
00:48:13,261 --> 00:48:16,515
Every day is a great day
when you are here.

401
00:48:16,598 --> 00:48:21,228
Today...
is your most fortunate day.

402
00:48:23,647 --> 00:48:26,066
Those giraffes
you sold me...

403
00:48:26,149 --> 00:48:28,109
they won't mate.

404
00:48:28,151 --> 00:48:32,781
They just walk around
eating and not mating.

405
00:48:32,822 --> 00:48:36,243
You sold me...
queer giraffes.

406
00:48:36,326 --> 00:48:40,664
- I want my money back.
- Not a chance.

407
00:48:42,666 --> 00:48:46,378
- I do special price for you.
- On what?

408
00:48:48,171 --> 00:48:50,799
Have you seen my new stock?
Come and see them.

409
00:49:04,938 --> 00:49:07,732
Do any of them fight?
I've got a match coming up.

410
00:49:07,774 --> 00:49:10,485
Some are good for fighting,
others for dying.

411
00:49:10,569 --> 00:49:12,571
You need both, I think.

412
00:49:12,654 --> 00:49:14,614
Get up!

413
00:49:21,955 --> 00:49:25,917
- What's your trade?
- I was a hunter.

414
00:49:26,001 --> 00:49:29,921
Oh, no. I bought him
from a salt mine in Carthage.

415
00:49:29,963 --> 00:49:32,257
Sit down!

416
00:49:35,969 --> 00:49:38,263
Mark of the legion.

417
00:49:38,305 --> 00:49:41,433
- Deserter.
- Maybe so. But who cares?

418
00:49:41,474 --> 00:49:43,602
- He's a Spaniard.
- I'll take six...

419
00:49:43,685 --> 00:49:45,645
- for 1 ,000.
- 1,000?

420
00:49:45,687 --> 00:49:47,898
The Numidian alone
is worth 2,000!

421
00:49:47,981 --> 00:49:50,650
These slaves
are rotten.

422
00:49:50,734 --> 00:49:52,944
It all adds to the flavor.
No. No, no, no. Wait-Wait.

423
00:49:53,028 --> 00:49:56,948
Wait! Can negotiate.

424
00:49:57,032 --> 00:50:01,494
I'll give you 2,000...
and four for the beasts.

425
00:50:01,578 --> 00:50:05,081
That's 5,000
for an old friend.

426
00:50:21,056 --> 00:50:23,725
Come on! How long does it take
to get into my own house?

427
00:50:23,767 --> 00:50:26,603
I am Proximo!

428
00:50:26,686 --> 00:50:29,689
I shall be closer to you
for the next few days,

429
00:50:29,773 --> 00:50:33,318
which will be last of your miserable
lives, than that bitch of a mother...

430
00:50:33,401 --> 00:50:36,321
- that brought you screaming
into this world!

431
00:50:36,404 --> 00:50:40,283
I did not pay good money
for you for your company!

432
00:50:40,367 --> 00:50:45,705
- I paid it so that I could
profit from your death.

433
00:50:45,789 --> 00:50:49,543
And as your mother
was there at your beginning,

434
00:50:49,626 --> 00:50:52,921
so I shall be there
at your end.

435
00:50:52,963 --> 00:50:57,676
- And when you die, and die you shall,

436
00:50:57,759 --> 00:51:00,720
your transition shall be
to the sound of-

437
00:51:05,851 --> 00:51:09,521
Gladiators, I salute you.

438
00:51:13,859 --> 00:51:16,570
-Red!
-Red.

439
00:51:16,653 --> 00:51:20,907
- Yellow!

440
00:51:20,991 --> 00:51:23,410
Yellow.

441
00:51:31,877 --> 00:51:33,044
Hyah!

442
00:51:33,086 --> 00:51:35,422
Good.

443
00:51:35,505 --> 00:51:36,965
- Red.
- Red!

444
00:51:41,678 --> 00:51:43,597
Spaniard!

445
00:52:08,246 --> 00:52:11,082
- Uhh.

446
00:52:16,838 --> 00:52:19,257
That's enough
for the moment!

447
00:52:19,341 --> 00:52:21,843
His time will come.

448
00:52:22,928 --> 00:52:25,138
Next!

449
00:52:38,360 --> 00:52:42,697
Spaniard, why don't you fight?

450
00:52:42,739 --> 00:52:45,367
We all have to fight.

451
00:52:58,755 --> 00:53:00,799
Is that the sign
of your gods?

452
00:53:05,971 --> 00:53:09,057
Will that not anger them?

453
00:53:29,703 --> 00:53:31,705
The gods favor you.

454
00:53:31,788 --> 00:53:34,749
Red is the gods' color.

455
00:53:34,833 --> 00:53:38,169
You will need
their help today.

456
00:53:54,686 --> 00:53:58,523
Some of you are thinking
you won't fight.

457
00:53:58,607 --> 00:54:00,942
Some that you can't fight.

458
00:54:02,402 --> 00:54:06,406
They all say that,
until they're out there.

459
00:54:08,408 --> 00:54:11,369
- Listen.
-Kill. Kill. Kill.

460
00:54:11,411 --> 00:54:13,914
Kill. Kill. Kill.

461
00:54:19,586 --> 00:54:22,047
Thrust this
into another man's flesh,

462
00:54:22,130 --> 00:54:25,008
and then they will applaud
and love you for that.

463
00:54:25,091 --> 00:54:28,345
You-

464
00:54:28,428 --> 00:54:30,764
You may begin
to love them...

465
00:54:30,805 --> 00:54:33,642
for that.

466
00:54:37,020 --> 00:54:41,191
Ultimately,
we're all dead men.

467
00:54:42,943 --> 00:54:46,696
Sadly, we cannot
choose how, but...

468
00:54:46,780 --> 00:54:50,367
we can decide how
we meet that end...

469
00:54:50,450 --> 00:54:54,329
in order that
we are remembered...

470
00:54:54,412 --> 00:54:56,373
as men.

471
00:55:00,752 --> 00:55:03,505
On the left,
draw your shields!

472
00:55:03,547 --> 00:55:06,591
On the right,
draw your swords!

473
00:55:06,675 --> 00:55:08,635
-Kill. Kill-

474
00:55:09,845 --> 00:55:13,849
Pair them up-
red with yellow.

475
00:55:16,977 --> 00:55:18,311
Next!

476
00:55:21,815 --> 00:55:23,233
Next!

477
00:57:17,347 --> 00:57:19,516
- Hyah! Hyah!

478
00:59:06,706 --> 00:59:09,376
- Go away!

479
00:59:39,531 --> 00:59:42,659
He enters Rome
like a conquering hero.

480
00:59:42,742 --> 00:59:44,703
But what
has he conquered?

481
00:59:44,786 --> 00:59:47,789
Give him time, Gracchus.
He's young.

482
00:59:47,873 --> 00:59:49,833
I think he could do very well.

483
00:59:49,875 --> 00:59:51,835
For Rome or for you?

484
00:59:57,924 --> 01:00:00,677
Go to your mother, Lucius.
It's what she'd like.

485
01:00:07,309 --> 01:00:11,021
- Lucius!
- Mother!

486
01:00:12,063 --> 01:00:16,193
- Hail, Caesar.
- Senators.

487
01:00:18,987 --> 01:00:21,865
Rome greets
her new emperor.

488
01:00:21,907 --> 01:00:25,410
Your loyal subjects
bid you welcome, Highness.

489
01:00:25,493 --> 01:00:28,914
Thank you, Falco.
And for the loyal subjects,

490
01:00:28,955 --> 01:00:32,459
- I trust they weren't too expensive.
- Caesar.

491
01:00:32,542 --> 01:00:36,630
- Gracchus.
- All Rome rejoices
in your return, Caesar.

492
01:00:36,713 --> 01:00:38,882
There are many matters
that require your attention.

493
01:00:42,385 --> 01:00:45,388
- To order! To order!

494
01:00:45,430 --> 01:00:50,185
For your guidance, Caesar, the Senate
has prepared a series of protocols...

495
01:00:50,268 --> 01:00:53,688
to begin addressing
the many problems in the city.

496
01:00:53,772 --> 01:00:57,943
Beginning with basic sanitation
for the Greek quarter...

497
01:00:58,026 --> 01:01:01,154
to combat the plague which is already
springing up there.

498
01:01:01,238 --> 01:01:04,658
- So, if Caesar-
- Shah.

499
01:01:05,825 --> 01:01:08,870
Don't you see, Gracchus?

500
01:01:08,954 --> 01:01:11,164
That's the very problem,
isn't it?

501
01:01:11,248 --> 01:01:14,334
My father spent
all his time at study...

502
01:01:16,127 --> 01:01:19,965
of books and learning
and philosophy.

503
01:01:20,006 --> 01:01:25,095
He spent his twilight hours
reading scrolls from the Senate.

504
01:01:25,178 --> 01:01:28,515
And all the while,
the people have forgotten-

505
01:01:28,598 --> 01:01:31,017
But the Senate
is the People, sire.

506
01:01:31,059 --> 01:01:34,813
Chosen from among the people...
to speak for the people.

507
01:01:34,896 --> 01:01:39,484
I doubt that many of the people
eat so well as you do, Gracchus.

508
01:01:39,568 --> 01:01:44,739
Or have such splendid mistresses, Gaius.
I think I understand my own people.

509
01:01:44,823 --> 01:01:48,535
Then, perhaps Caesar will
be so good as to teach us...

510
01:01:48,618 --> 01:01:50,871
out of his own
extensive experience.

511
01:01:54,749 --> 01:01:56,751
- I call it love.

512
01:01:56,793 --> 01:02:00,714
- I am their father.
The people are my children.

513
01:02:00,797 --> 01:02:03,008
And I shall hold them to my bosom
and embrace them tightly.

